ineteenth and twentieth centuries, presenting the narratives, representations, and geographic conceptions of the region that existed in these two national cultures. The volume shows how knowledge about "their own" space ended up serving as a tool for both Lithuanian and German political aspirations and how it challenged the spatial concepts about this area in the previous century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Dez 2019) 0aEthnic groupszLithuania Minor (Russia and Lithuania). 0aEthnic groupszPrussia, East (Poland and Russia). 0aMulticulturalismzLithuania Minor (Russia and Lithuania). 0aMulticulturalismzPrussia, East (Poland and Russia). 0aNationalismzLithuania Minor (Russia and Lithuania). 0aNationalismzPrussia, East (Poland and Russia). 7aHISTORY / Europe / Baltic States.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertASP eBook Package 2016z978311068816040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781618115256zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781618115256.jpg  a978-3-11-068816-0  ASP eBook Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_HICS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_HICS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG